Problem set 4: Movie budgets

S470/670

Spring 2018

Read the data and load packages:

movie_budgets = read.table("movie_budgets.txt", header=TRUE)
library(ggplot2)
library(broom)

Add a logged budget variable for convenience:

movie_budgets = data.frame(movie_budgets, log10_budget = log10(movie_budgets$budget))

Do a rough check for linearity:

ggplot(movie_budgets, aes(x=year, y=log10_budget)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()

ggplot(movie_budgets, aes(x=length, y=log10_budget)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()

Logged budget is pretty obviously nonlinear in year. It looks nonlinear in length as well, though this is in large part because of a small proportion of extremely long movies (over 150 minutes.) Nevertheless, itll be safer to fit a loess model rather than a linear model. The data doesnt look nice (there are outliers all over the place) so itll be safer to do a robust fit using family = "symmetric".

Do we need an interaction? Its a judgment call including the interaction necessarily improves the fit, but increases the complexity and complicates interpretation. In this case our model isnt too complicated, so IMHO we might as well throw it in.

What about the span of the loess fit? Keep reducing it until you get residuals that look randomly scattered around zero in all relevant plots, making sure that the final fit you end up with is reasonably smooth. I found 0.15 worked well.

budget.lo = loess(log10_budget ~ year * length, span = 0.15, family = "symmetric", data = movie_budgets)
budget.lo.df = augment(budget.lo)
ggplot(budget.lo.df, aes(x=year, y=.resid)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "loess", method.args = list(family = "symmetric"))

ggplot(budget.lo.df, aes(x=length, y=.resid)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "loess", method.args = list(family = "symmetric"))

ggplot(budget.lo.df, aes(x=year, y=.resid)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~cut_number(length, n=9), ncol=3) + geom_smooth(method.args = list(family = "symmetric"))

ggplot(budget.lo.df, aes(x=length, y=.resid)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~cut_number(year, n=9), ncol=3) + geom_smooth(method.args = list(family = "symmetric"))

Now display the fit. To me personally the relationship with length is more interesting, so Ill condition on length and plot fitted logged budget against year. Ill concentrate my grid points where theres data (i.e.there are hardly any movies longer than 150 minutes so lets forget about them.)

movie.grid = expand.grid(length=1:150, year=seq(1930,2000,10))
movie.predict = predict(budget.lo, newdata=movie.grid)
ggplot(data.frame(movie.grid, log10_budget=as.vector(movie.predict)), aes(x=length, y=log10_budget)) + geom_line() + facet_wrap(~year, ncol=2) + labs(title="Fitted log10 movie budget vs. length, conditional on year")

The increase in log budget with length does seems to be sub-linear (which makes sense since budget is logged; you wouldnt expect making your movie \(x\) minutes longer would make it \(y\) times more expensive. A transformation of length wouldve been sensible here.) Inflation in movie budgets is more pronounced for full-length movies than for shorts.

Lets draw a contour plot because I dont really like wireframes:

movie.contour.grid = expand.grid(length=1:150, year=1925:2005)
movie.contour.predict = predict(budget.lo, newdata=movie.contour.grid)
ggplot(data.frame(movie.contour.grid, log10_budget=as.vector(movie.contour.predict)), aes(x=year, y=length, z=log10_budget, fill=log10_budget)) + geom_raster()  + geom_contour(breaks = 4:7, color="black") + scale_fill_distiller(palette="RdBu")

We can interpret the contours as how much movie a dollar amount buys. So a million dollars (the 6 contour) used to get you a 150-minute epic, but now barely buys a 90 minute cheapie. The uptick in contours/decrease in budgets in recent years is probably just selection bias: recent low-budget movies are more likely to be in the data set than old low-budget movies.
